===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{liushu|i}} – a differentiated form ({{zh-l|*分化字}}) of {{och-l|高|high, tall}}, with a differentiating marker, which was variously a stroke, {{zh-l|*屮}}, {{zh-l|*止}}, {{zh-l|*力}}, {{zh-l|*九}}{{,}} or {{zh-l|*夭}}.

Based on the {{zh-l|*夭}} form, only attested starting from the {{w|Han dynasty}} ({{zh-ref|Chi, 2010}}), ''{{w|Shuowen}}'' erroneously interprets {{zh-l|*夭}} as a semantic component meaning “to bend” and treats the character as a {{liushu|psc|nocap=1}}.

===Etymology 1===
{{zh-forms|s=乔|alt=𠳮}}

Cognate with {{och-l|憍|id=1|to lift the head}}, {{och-l|驕|proud}}, {{och-l|撟|id=2|to lift}}, {{och-l|嶠|peak}}; {{och-l|高|high; tall}} and {{och-l|蹻|id=1|martial; vigorous}} could be allofams ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).

{{zh-ref|Sagart (2017b)}} compares this word to {{cog|bo|སྒྲོ||to elevate; to exalt; to increase}} and {{cog|kac|shagrau||to exalt}}. He also considers {{och-l|鷮|a kind of pheasant (with a long tail and feathers used for ornaments)}} to be related, comparing it to {{cog|bo|སྒྲོ||large feather}}, which he suggests is derived from the verb.

